259
00:22:30,312 --> 00:22:33,557
...five, six, seven

260
00:22:35,552 --> 00:22:37,079
eight, nine...

261
00:22:49,551 --> 00:22:53,080
The standard SS rate for
jewish skilled labourers is seven marks a day

262
00:22:53,550 --> 00:22:55,236
five for unskilled and women.

263
00:22:56,350 --> 00:22:59,378
This
is what you pay the Reich Economic Office.

264
00:22:59,436 --> 00:23:01,432
The jews themselves receive nothing.

265
00:23:02,267 --> 00:23:03,483
Poles: you pay wages.

266
00:23:04,301 --> 00:23:05,914
Generally they get a little more.

267
00:23:06,223 --> 00:23:07,131
Are you listening?

268
00:23:07,312 --> 00:23:08,631
What was that about the SS?

269
00:23:08,789 --> 00:23:10,417
The rate? The what?

270
00:23:11,069 --> 00:23:12,167
The jewish worker's salary.

271
00:23:12,226 --> 00:23:14,271
You pay it
directly to the SS, not to the worker.

272
00:23:14,329 --> 00:23:16,228
- He gets nothing.
- But it's less.

273
00:23:16,363 --> 00:23:17,834
It's less than what I would pay a Pole.

274
00:23:17,892 --> 00:23:18,515
It's less.

275
00:23:18,695 --> 00:23:20,314
That's the point I'm trying to make.

276
00:23:21,780 --> 00:23:22,831
Poles cost more.

277
00:23:25,026 --> 00:23:26,747
Why should I hire Poles?

278
00:23:28,467 --> 00:23:31,589
An enamelware factory over at Lipowa Street.

279
00:23:33,628 --> 00:23:35,044
It's owned by a German

280
00:23:35,102 --> 00:23:38,908
but it's outside the ghetto,
so you can barter for extra goods

281
00:23:38,987 --> 00:23:40,435
for eggs, I don't know what you need

282
00:23:40,493 --> 00:23:42,113
with
the Polish workers. You can't get it here.

283
00:23:42,427 --> 00:23:45,793
Also,
he's asking for 10 healthy women for the...

284
00:23:45,851 --> 00:23:46,715
I am healthy.

285
00:23:48,140 --> 00:23:49,504
Bring your sister, OK?

286
00:23:54,811 --> 00:23:55,627
Come.

287
00:23:56,251 --> 00:23:58,007
You need to convince them you have a trade

288
00:23:58,065 --> 00:23:59,542
something valuable to the war effort.

289
00:23:59,601 --> 00:24:00,238
- Like what?
- What if you don't?

290
00:24:00,342 --> 00:24:01,309
I'm a musician.

291
00:24:01,988 --> 00:24:02,898
Your name goes on a list.

292
00:24:02,963 --> 00:24:05,149
I hear your name
goes on a list and they put you on trucks...

293
00:24:05,225 --> 00:24:07,146
- No no. That's not true.
- You're a musician?

294
00:24:07,225 --> 00:24:08,242
- Lisa
- Yeah

295
00:24:08,300 --> 00:24:09,754
I'd find a good hiding place if I were you.

296
00:24:09,813 --> 00:24:11,592
I'm not going to hide like some animal.

297
00:24:12,291 --> 00:24:13,534
There are places to hide.

298
00:24:20,666 --> 00:24:22,821
I'm a graduate of the University of Lviv.

299
00:24:24,232 --> 00:24:26,838
I used to work
at the hydroelectric station in Roznow.

300
00:24:26,905 --> 00:24:27,797
Blue card

301
00:24:32,214 --> 00:24:33,645
I'm going to get the necessary papers

302
00:24:33,879 --> 00:24:35,560
because this card is no good anymore.

303
00:24:36,050 --> 00:24:38,389
You can stay in this line
all day. You'll still get one of these.

304
00:24:38,446 --> 00:24:41,896
They are
no good. You'll have to leave the line now.

305
00:24:42,112 --> 00:24:44,089
Then you'll get a blue card, a <i>blauschein</i>

306
00:24:44,496 --> 00:24:46,472
to say that you are an essential worker.

307
00:24:46,543 --> 00:24:48,828
I'll get these papers for you at Pankiewicz.

308
00:24:49,847 --> 00:24:51,228
Pharmacist. Just there, look.

309
00:24:52,168 --> 00:24:52,789
Guess who is here?

310
00:24:53,343 --> 00:24:56,026
Poldek. Enjoying the weather, Poldek?

311
00:24:56,103 --> 00:24:57,099
Enjoying the lines?

312
00:24:57,427 --> 00:24:58,715
Need some shoe polish?

313
00:24:58,901 --> 00:25:00,030
In a metal container maybe?

314
00:25:01,533 --> 00:25:02,553
Not essential?

315
00:25:02,957 --> 00:25:05,672
I think
you misunderstand the meaning of the word.

316
00:25:06,103 --> 00:25:07,532
No blue card, sir.

317
00:25:07,617 --> 00:25:09,876
Stand over there. Move. Next.

318
00:25:11,478 --> 00:25:12,987
What do you mean, "not essential"?

319
00:25:14,542 --> 00:25:16,668
I teach history and literature.

320
00:25:17,282 --> 00:25:18,922
Since when it's not essential?

321
00:25:24,516 --> 00:25:25,672
He's a metal polisher.

322
00:25:33,537 --> 00:25:34,431
It was not right?

323
00:25:34,489 --> 00:25:36,018
It's very good. He's 53 years old.

324
00:25:36,077 --> 00:25:37,029
It's too new.

325
00:25:37,119 --> 00:25:38,112
Mmm thank you.

326
00:25:46,873 --> 00:25:48,793
You're crazy. You left it in your drawer.

327
00:25:49,306 --> 00:25:50,897
How many times have I told you?

328
00:25:51,421 --> 00:25:54,137
"Your work certificate
you keep in your pocket at all times"

329
00:25:54,301 --> 00:25:57,629
and you leave yours
in your drawer! How many times I've told you?

330
00:25:59,130 --> 00:26:00,553
I'm a metal polisher.

331
00:26:09,630 --> 00:26:11,996
Take the round sheet of tin

332
00:26:13,441 --> 00:26:15,801
dip it in soap emulsion

333
00:26:17,178 --> 00:26:20,382
then place it centrally in the press.

334
00:26:35,821 --> 00:26:37,128
We obtain the soup pot.

335
00:26:38,093 --> 00:26:38,921
...the soup pot.

336
00:26:39,540 --> 00:26:40,541
...soup pot.

337
00:26:42,899 --> 00:26:44,505
Grosz, Mrs. Grosz, stay together.

338
00:26:49,540 --> 00:26:52,555
Sir, I have 10 work permits here

339
00:26:52,613 --> 00:26:54,667
for the Deutsche Emailwarenfabrik.

340
00:26:57,698 --> 00:27:01,495
If it's carbonized, clean it with a file

341
00:27:02,619 --> 00:27:06,359
but don't touch
both the electrodes at the same time.

342
00:27:06,777 --> 00:27:09,582
You'll get electrocuted. Here. Have a try.

343
00:27:13,898 --> 00:27:15,792
Roll the metal under the press

344
00:27:16,301 --> 00:27:18,625
but
be very careful unless you want your fingers

345
00:27:18,700 --> 00:27:20,467
to become part of the teapot.

346
00:27:23,018 --> 00:27:23,758
Occupation?

347
00:27:23,997 --> 00:27:26,387
I'm a writer. I play the flute.

348
00:27:26,446 --> 00:27:29,936
But Moses is a skilled metalworker.

349
00:27:29,994 --> 00:27:32,007
He can make tin pots. He can make tanks.

350
00:27:32,066 --> 00:27:33,821
He can make whatever Mr. Schindler asks.

351
00:27:33,899 --> 00:27:37,728
He's highly skilled. Give him
your card. Moses, give him your card.

352
00:27:40,841 --> 00:27:44,902
Now, dip the basin
with the tongs into the enamel solution

353
00:27:47,498 --> 00:27:51,457
and after swivelling it around,
carefully place it aside to drip dry.

354
00:27:54,738 --> 00:27:56,356
And whatever he asks you, allow me

355
00:27:56,415 --> 00:27:58,378
just to represent you and speak for you.

356
00:27:58,458 --> 00:27:59,867
Don't say a word.

357
00:28:00,339 --> 00:28:03,545
Filing, billing,
keeping track of my appointments, shorthand

358
00:28:03,765 --> 00:28:05,848
typing, obviously... How is your typing?

359
00:28:06,968 --> 00:28:07,739
Uh all right.

360
00:28:07,800 --> 00:28:08,311
Please

361
00:29:00,457 --> 00:29:02,378
You need a secretary. Pick one.

362
00:29:04,334 --> 00:29:07,456
I don't know how. They're all so... qualified.

363
00:29:08,927 --> 00:29:10,166
You have to choose.

364
00:29:13,598 --> 00:29:14,514
Please give a nice smile.

365
00:29:14,572 --> 00:29:15,948
Big smile. Big smile.

366
00:29:16,014 --> 00:29:16,864
Attention.

367
00:29:36,253 --> 00:29:38,723
If you would, look after my guest.

368
00:29:40,497 --> 00:29:43,427
Boxed teas are good. Coffee, pate

369
00:29:44,652 --> 00:29:47,380
kielbasa sausage, cheeses, Beluga caviar.

370
00:29:48,091 --> 00:29:49,061
- Yes
- And of course

371
00:29:49,132 --> 00:29:50,195
who could live without German cigarettes?

372
00:29:50,253 --> 00:29:51,677
Get me as many as you can find

373
00:29:52,650 --> 00:29:53,771
and some more fresh fruit

374
00:29:54,734 --> 00:29:56,901
the real
rarities: oranges, lemons, pineapples.

375
00:29:57,503 --> 00:29:59,777
I need
several boxes of Cuban cigars, the best

376
00:30:00,212 --> 00:30:01,474
yes and dark, unsweetened chocolate.

377
00:30:01,652 --> 00:30:03,688
not in the shape
of lady fingers, the chunk chocolate

378
00:30:03,771 --> 00:30:05,479
big as my hand, you sample at wine tastings.

379
00:30:06,154 --> 00:30:06,731
Yes

380
00:30:06,851 --> 00:30:09,550
We're going to
need lots of cognac, the best: Hennessy

381
00:30:10,010 --> 00:30:11,205
Dom Perignon champagne.

382
00:30:12,710 --> 00:30:14,191
Get L'Espadon sardines

383
00:30:14,649 --> 00:30:17,694
and oh, try to find nylon stockings.

384
00:30:21,090 --> 00:30:23,725
<i>It is my distinct pleasure to announce</i>

385
00:30:23,890 --> 00:30:28,832
<i>the fully operational
status of Deutsche Emailwarenfabrik</i>

386
00:30:29,210 --> 00:30:29,899
See some rags.

387
00:30:29,957 --> 00:30:33,525
<i>Manufacturers
of superior enamelware crockery</i>

388
00:30:34,448 --> 00:30:38,407
<i>expressly
designed and crafted for military use</i>

389
00:30:39,369 --> 00:30:41,728
<i>utilizing only the most modern equipment.</i>

390
00:30:41,871 --> 00:30:44,302
<i>D.E.F.'s staff of highly skilled and</i>

391
00:30:44,361 --> 00:30:46,536
<i>experienced artisans and journeymen</i>

392
00:30:46,801 --> 00:30:49,545
<i>deliver a product of unparalleled quality</i>

393
00:30:50,329 --> 00:30:53,917
<i>enabling me
to proffer, with absolute confidence and pride</i>

394
00:30:54,137 --> 00:30:56,590
<i>a full line of field and kitchenware</i>

395
00:30:56,649 --> 00:30:59,527
<i>unsurpassable
in all respects by my competitors.</i>

396
00:31:00,774 --> 00:31:03,023
<i>See attached list and available colours.</i>

397
00:31:04,647 --> 00:31:07,527
<i>Anticipating
the enclosed bids will meet with your approval</i>

398
00:31:08,085 --> 00:31:11,492
<i>and looking forward
to a long and mutually prosperous association</i>

399
00:31:11,887 --> 00:31:14,813
<i>I extend
to you in advance my sincerest gratitude</i>

400
00:31:14,904 --> 00:31:16,387
<i>and very best regards.</i>

401
00:31:16,670 --> 00:31:17,617
<i>Oskar Schindler.</i>

402
00:31:17,771 --> 00:31:20,774
Yeah. I need
700 gross from here for next Thursday.

403
00:31:21,085 --> 00:31:23,604
Nine hundred...
No. Make it 10 for Wednesday.

404
00:31:23,665 --> 00:31:25,431
All this stuff here goes to Madritsch's

405
00:31:25,489 --> 00:31:27,257
factory on Tuesday of next week.

406
00:31:43,005 --> 00:31:45,622
My father was fond
of saying, "You need three things in life:

407
00:31:46,459 --> 00:31:47,500
"a good doctor

408
00:31:48,319 --> 00:31:49,752
"a forgiving priest

409
00:31:50,598 --> 00:31:51,928
"and a clever accountant."

410
00:31:56,564 --> 00:31:57,724
The first two

411
00:31:58,660 --> 00:32:00,266
I've never had much use for

412
00:32:00,573 --> 00:32:02,335
but the third...

413
00:32:09,285 --> 00:32:11,805
Just pretend, for Christ's sake.

414
00:32:16,209 --> 00:32:17,029
Is that all?

415
00:32:23,765 --> 00:32:24,948
I'm trying to thank you.

416
00:32:27,333 --> 00:32:29,680
I'm saying,
I couldn't have done this without you.

417
00:32:33,450 --> 00:32:35,868
The usual thing
would be to acknowledge my gratitude.

418
00:32:35,952 --> 00:32:37,989
It would also,
by the way, be the courteous thing.

419
00:32:40,965 --> 00:32:41,811
You're welcome.

420
00:32:52,149 --> 00:32:52,897
Get out of here.

421
00:33:06,843 --> 00:33:08,835
Klonowska, who is it?

422
00:33:19,003 --> 00:33:20,771
She's so embarrassed. Look at her.

423
00:33:33,120 --> 00:33:34,675
You know something? You would like her.

424
00:33:35,282 --> 00:33:36,498
- Oskar, please
- What?

425
00:33:37,250 --> 00:33:38,698
I don't
have to like her just because you do.

426
00:33:38,757 --> 00:33:39,447
You would, though.

427
00:33:39,505 --> 00:33:40,591
It doesn't work that way.

428
00:33:54,977 --> 00:33:56,158
You've done well here.

429
00:33:59,566 --> 00:34:00,654
You look wonderful.

430
00:34:04,760 --> 00:34:06,287
Be careful of the step, miss.

431
00:34:06,640 --> 00:34:07,849
Mrs. Schindler, Marek

432
00:34:20,800 --> 00:34:22,164
It's not a charade, all this?

433
00:34:22,699 --> 00:34:24,326
A charade? How could it be a charade?

434
00:34:24,387 --> 00:34:25,628
The clothes, the car, the apartment...

435
00:34:25,686 --> 00:34:26,527
Wait a minute.

436
00:34:26,585 --> 00:34:29,280
Take a guess.
How many people are on my payroll?

437
00:34:29,360 --> 00:34:30,286
Oskar

438
00:34:30,833 --> 00:34:34,927
My father, at the height
of his success, had 50. I've got 350

439
00:34:35,907 --> 00:34:37,179
350 workers

440
00:34:37,237 --> 00:34:39,367
on the factory floor, with one purpose:

441
00:34:40,559 --> 00:34:41,896
...to make pots and pans?

442
00:34:42,358 --> 00:34:43,311
...to make money

443
00:34:44,199 --> 00:34:44,882
for me.

444
00:34:51,878 --> 00:34:54,364
Does anyone ask about me?

445
00:34:56,318 --> 00:34:57,179
Back home?

446
00:34:58,310 --> 00:34:59,205
Everybody

447
00:34:59,358 --> 00:35:00,476
all the time.

448
00:35:02,233 --> 00:35:02,822
Hmm

449
00:35:06,239 --> 00:35:09,978
They won't soon forget the name,
Schindler here. I can tell you that.

450
00:35:12,318 --> 00:35:14,565
"Oskar Schindler," they'll say.

451
00:35:15,318 --> 00:35:17,072
"Everybody remembers him.

452
00:35:19,237 --> 00:35:21,956
"He did something extraordinary.

453
00:35:23,837 --> 00:35:25,664
"He did something no one else did.

454
00:35:28,596 --> 00:35:30,132
"He came here with nothing

455
00:35:31,476 --> 00:35:32,567
"a suitcase

456
00:35:34,076 --> 00:35:38,201
"and built
a bankrupt company into a major manufactory.

457
00:35:40,237 --> 00:35:42,243
"and left with a steamer trunk

458
00:35:43,155 --> 00:35:45,590
"two steamer trunks full of money

459
00:35:48,022 --> 00:35:49,764
"all the riches of the world."

460
00:35:52,114 --> 00:35:52,788
Hmm

461
00:35:53,956 --> 00:35:56,578
It's
comforting to see that nothing's changed.

462
00:35:56,835 --> 00:35:58,480
You're wrong, Emilie.

463
00:36:00,868 --> 00:36:03,021
There's
no way I could have known this before

464
00:36:03,514 --> 00:36:05,130
but there was always something missing.

465
00:36:10,094 --> 00:36:11,464
Something was missing.

466
00:36:13,099 --> 00:36:14,449
Even if I'd known what it was

467
00:36:14,509 --> 00:36:17,047
there's nothing
I could have done about it because

468
00:36:18,230 --> 00:36:19,772
you can't create this thing

469
00:36:21,114 --> 00:36:24,802
and it makes all the difference
in the world between success and failure.

470
00:36:26,949 --> 00:36:27,585
Luck?

471
00:36:30,853 --> 00:36:31,677
War!

472
00:36:56,404 --> 00:36:57,643
Should I stay?

473
00:37:00,472 --> 00:37:01,795
It's a beautiful city.

474
00:37:04,630 --> 00:37:06,168
I asked you if I should stay.

475
00:37:09,707 --> 00:37:10,629
It's up to you.

476
00:37:16,234 --> 00:37:17,278
Promise me, Oskar

477
00:37:17,957 --> 00:37:20,345
no doorman or maitre d' will ever presume

478
00:37:20,432 --> 00:37:22,142
I'm anyone other than Mrs. Schindler

479
00:37:23,004 --> 00:37:23,990
and I'll stay.

480
00:37:27,718 --> 00:37:28,689
Goodbye, darling

481
00:37:45,752 --> 00:37:48,927
I could try to read this
or I could eat my lunch while it's still hot.

482
00:37:50,575 --> 00:37:51,512
We're doing well?

483
00:37:51,751 --> 00:37:52,995
- Yes
- Better this month than last?

484
00:37:53,071 --> 00:37:53,515
Yes

485
00:37:53,573 --> 00:37:55,325
Any reason to think next month will be worse?

486
00:37:55,383 --> 00:37:56,492
The war could end.

487
00:38:08,240 --> 00:38:08,752
What?

488
00:38:09,091 --> 00:38:10,452
There is a machinist outside

489
00:38:10,510 --> 00:38:12,762
who'd like
to thank you personally for giving him a job.

490
00:38:13,908 --> 00:38:14,736
Every day he comes.

491
00:38:15,051 --> 00:38:17,046
He's very grateful. It'll just take a minute.

492
00:38:24,234 --> 00:38:25,298
Mr. Lowenstein?

493
00:38:33,135 --> 00:38:35,713
I want to thank you, sir

494
00:38:36,224 --> 00:38:38,631
for giving me the opportunity to work.

495
00:38:38,747 --> 00:38:40,925
You're welcome.
I'm sure you're doing a great job.

496
00:38:41,787 --> 00:38:45,936
The SS beat me up. They would have killed me

497
00:38:46,421 --> 00:38:49,834
but I am
essential to the war effort, thanks to you.

498
00:38:50,669 --> 00:38:51,392
That's great.

499
00:38:52,428 --> 00:38:54,394
I work hard for you.

500
00:38:54,682 --> 00:38:55,816
I'm sure you do.

501
00:38:55,876 --> 00:38:58,497
I'll continue to work hard for you.

502
00:38:59,307 --> 00:39:00,671
That's great. Thanks.

503
00:39:00,729 --> 00:39:01,776
God bless you, sir.

504
00:39:02,472 --> 00:39:03,207
All right.

505
00:39:03,265 --> 00:39:04,562
You are a good man.

506
00:39:08,385 --> 00:39:09,564
He saved my life.

507
00:39:09,622 --> 00:39:10,354
Yes, he did.

508
00:39:11,488 --> 00:39:12,320
God bless him.

509
00:39:12,378 --> 00:39:13,495
Yeah. Come on.

510
00:39:16,426 --> 00:39:17,675
God bless you.

511
00:39:30,378 --> 00:39:32,834
I'm sorry,
Herr Direktor, but you're running very late.

512
00:39:33,066 --> 00:39:36,162
This is for the Obersturmbannfuhrer, sir

513
00:39:36,220 --> 00:39:39,185
and this is
for his niece, Greta. It's her birthday.

514
00:39:39,243 --> 00:39:39,624
By the way

515
00:39:39,684 --> 00:39:40,531
Greta as in Garbo.

516
00:39:40,589 --> 00:39:42,356
don't ever do that to me again.

517
00:39:42,865 --> 00:39:44,392
Go go. drive. Don't bow.

518
00:39:44,466 --> 00:39:46,327
Did you happen to notice that
that man had one arm?

519
00:39:46,385 --> 00:39:47,115
